1
00:00:46,012 --> 00:00:49,948
"I lay on my pillow
at the Sherry-Netherland Hotel.

2
00:00:50,050 --> 00:00:53,042
"Delicious and destroyed.

3
00:00:53,153 --> 00:00:56,816
"Inhaling the fragrance of the sheets.

4
00:00:56,923 --> 00:01:01,053
"Feeling the warmth of where
you were just laying.

5
00:01:01,161 --> 00:01:03,789
"You make me new with laughter.

6
00:01:03,897 --> 00:01:06,263
"You make me old with wisdom.

7
00:01:07,767 --> 00:01:09,758
You make wine taste sweeter."

8
00:01:11,337 --> 00:01:12,702
Who wrote that?

9
00:01:14,240 --> 00:01:17,732
I write a lot of poetry when I'm inspired.

10
00:01:23,016 --> 00:01:26,611
I guess I shouldn't be surprised
by anything you do.

11
00:01:26,719 --> 00:01:28,118
You shouldn't.

12
00:01:29,656 --> 00:01:31,055
It's insulting.

13
00:01:34,294 --> 00:01:37,957
I have to keep you in line,
or I'll lose you.

14
00:01:38,064 --> 00:01:39,588
Yes, you will.

15
00:01:41,968 --> 00:01:44,232
I don't like the idea of making you older.

16
00:01:46,773 --> 00:01:48,798
I just meant...

17
00:01:51,778 --> 00:01:53,177
I don't know.

18
00:02:00,220 --> 00:02:03,747
It doesn't matter how old I am.

19
00:02:03,857 --> 00:02:05,916
Our souls are the same age.

20
00:02:21,774 --> 00:02:23,105
Oh, God.

21
00:02:25,812 --> 00:02:27,507
You're getting to me.

22
00:02:34,087 --> 00:02:37,420
How do I know I'm not just
going to eat another mushroom

23
00:02:37,524 --> 00:02:41,756
and this room will disappear
and I'll be back on a train to Trenton?

24
00:02:41,861 --> 00:02:44,694
Because I love you, Jane.

25
00:02:49,169 --> 00:02:52,229
This is hard for you. I know it.

26
00:02:55,308 --> 00:02:56,741
You don't want me to talk about it,

27
00:02:56,843 --> 00:03:02,179
but Margaret and Mona have been
your life for the last 40 years.

28
00:03:02,282 --> 00:03:04,147
30.

29
00:03:06,186 --> 00:03:09,747
Listen, I'm not being impulsive,

30
00:03:09,856 --> 00:03:12,757
because I've been thinking
about this all the time.

31
00:03:14,894 --> 00:03:17,158
I want you to be my wife.

32
00:03:18,231 --> 00:03:19,198
What?

33
00:03:21,034 --> 00:03:22,092
Marry me.

34
00:03:24,037 --> 00:03:25,595
Roger, are you serious?

35
00:03:25,705 --> 00:03:27,434
Will you do that for me?

36
00:03:42,422 --> 00:03:45,516
90% of Right Guard users
say they play sports.

37
00:03:45,625 --> 00:03:47,718
60% wear it for their girls as well.

38
00:03:47,827 --> 00:03:51,888
Most impressive, 80% of the fellas
saying "yes" to the question:

39
00:03:51,998 --> 00:03:54,762
"Does Right Guard make you
feel more confident at work?"

40
00:03:54,867 --> 00:03:57,097
Did anyone watch Loretta Young last night?

41
00:03:57,203 --> 00:03:58,636
I was supposed to. What happened?

42
00:03:58,738 --> 00:04:01,366
I can't even describe it, it was so awful.

43
00:04:01,474 --> 00:04:05,911
Creative, think old Donnie Draper will mind
if we think better on a full stomach?

44
00:04:07,647 --> 00:04:09,547
Well, if you'll all swear
Gillette dropped in.

45
00:04:09,649 --> 00:04:11,344
Are you kidding?

46
00:04:11,451 --> 00:04:13,043
Absolutely.

47
00:04:13,152 --> 00:04:15,177
I'll pretend they're here if you give me
some actual ideas.

48
00:04:15,288 --> 00:04:17,620
Right Guard already has
a great campaign...

49
00:04:17,724 --> 00:04:18,884
men being men.

50
00:04:18,992 --> 00:04:20,721
You know, women smell bad, too.

51
00:04:20,827 --> 00:04:22,021
Not you, of course.

52
00:04:22,128 --> 00:04:23,390
Women have perfume.

53
00:04:23,496 --> 00:04:25,862
"Perfume does not fight wetness."

54
00:04:25,965 --> 00:04:28,729
Loretta Young.
She's my dad's favorite.

55
00:04:28,835 --> 00:04:30,029
The aprons.

56
00:04:30,136 --> 00:04:32,570
The nauseating upholstery on the couch.

57
00:04:32,672 --> 00:04:34,503
Strangers who drop by.

58
00:04:34,607 --> 00:04:35,596
Hear from Kinsey?

59
00:04:35,708 --> 00:04:37,073
What do you mean?

60
00:04:37,176 --> 00:04:38,700
Did you read what's going on down there?

61
00:04:38,811 --> 00:04:40,369
In this day and age.

62
00:04:40,480 --> 00:04:42,675
The papers said it's gonna be
Little Rock all over again.

63
00:04:42,782 --> 00:04:45,307
I don't know why people
keep stirring up trouble.

64
00:04:45,418 --> 00:04:46,612
It's bad for business.

65
00:04:46,719 --> 00:04:47,981
Just another reason not to watch TV.

66
00:04:48,087 --> 00:04:49,520
Kurt doesn't even have one.

67
00:04:49,622 --> 00:04:51,249
You have to have one. It's your job.

68
00:04:51,357 --> 00:04:52,551
You're gonna miss the playoff.

69
00:04:54,160 --> 00:04:55,559
It's a different life for single men.

70
00:04:55,662 --> 00:04:57,789
What do you do with your spare time?

71
00:04:57,897 --> 00:05:00,058
I like concerts. I like park.

72
00:05:00,166 --> 00:05:01,963
He saw Bob Dylan at Carnegie Hall.

73
00:05:02,068 --> 00:05:03,865
I heard him on the radio.

74
00:05:03,970 --> 00:05:06,234
So we're not gonna work at all.

75
00:05:07,807 --> 00:05:10,640
Tell Right Guard,
short of a new product just for women,

76
00:05:10,743 --> 00:05:12,040
we need more research and time.

77
00:05:12,145 --> 00:05:13,169
And lunch.

78
00:05:15,381 --> 00:05:17,349
Can we split a lobster?

79
00:05:24,524 --> 00:05:26,549
Does he sound like the album?

80
00:05:26,659 --> 00:05:29,560
When you hear him, he plays it himself.

81
00:05:29,662 --> 00:05:31,755
He must be something to see.

82
00:05:31,864 --> 00:05:33,058
I'd love to go sometime.

83
00:05:33,166 --> 00:05:34,497
So go.

84
00:05:34,600 --> 00:05:35,999
Yes, I should.

85
00:05:36,102 --> 00:05:37,592
You will go with me.

86
00:05:37,704 --> 00:05:39,171
What?

87
00:05:39,272 --> 00:05:41,570
You would go with me?

88
00:05:41,674 --> 00:05:45,974
No. I don't want to impose
if you have plans.

89
00:05:46,079 --> 00:05:50,345
When you hear him, you will smile like this.

90
00:05:52,585 --> 00:05:53,882
Pick you up at 8.

91
00:05:53,986 --> 00:05:55,613
I live in Brooklyn. It's a hike.

92
00:05:55,722 --> 00:05:57,485
Neighbors.

93
00:05:59,092 --> 00:06:00,923
Joey says that Duck's in the blind.

94
00:06:01,027 --> 00:06:02,255
It's now or never.

95
00:06:23,549 --> 00:06:26,575
This is why I booked a day early.

96
00:06:26,686 --> 00:06:28,517
What did Ricardo in there say?

97
00:06:28,621 --> 00:06:30,714
He's in hourly contact with TWA,

98
00:06:30,823 --> 00:06:32,882
and they've offered
to buy you new luggage.

99
00:06:32,992 --> 00:06:34,721
And fill it with my things?

100
00:06:34,827 --> 00:06:38,194
Ricardo recommended a tailor. Chinese.

101
00:06:38,297 --> 00:06:42,028
And he said they've got
a whole shop full of swim trunks.

102
00:06:42,135 --> 00:06:44,000
I brought mine.

103
00:06:44,103 --> 00:06:46,333
There's not gonna be any swimming.

104
00:06:46,439 --> 00:06:49,340
The convention doesn't
start for another day.

105
00:06:49,442 --> 00:06:50,500
You want to be the hundredth person

106
00:06:50,610 --> 00:06:52,077
to shake someone's hand
at some convention?

107
00:06:52,178 --> 00:06:53,736
For what, a free pen?

108
00:06:53,846 --> 00:06:55,837
We'll follow up face to face.

109
00:06:55,948 --> 00:06:58,109
Forget Santa Monica.

110
00:06:58,217 --> 00:07:00,276
Take your list,
target some of these guys,

111
00:07:00,386 --> 00:07:02,047
and make them feel special.

112
00:07:02,155 --> 00:07:04,214
Didn't Roger give you leads?

113
00:07:04,323 --> 00:07:05,449
He did.

114
00:07:06,692 --> 00:07:08,250
I'm gonna need sunglasses.

115
00:07:12,832 --> 00:07:14,595
Come on.

116
00:07:14,700 --> 00:07:16,190
You want to be on vacation, Pete?

117
00:07:16,302 --> 00:07:17,894
Because I can make that happen.

118
00:08:08,621 --> 00:08:09,952
Old-fashioned.

119
00:08:13,359 --> 00:08:14,485
Excuse me.

120
00:08:15,862 --> 00:08:18,490
My friends and I have
been speculating about you,

121
00:08:18,598 --> 00:08:21,431
trying to decide who you are
and what you do.

122
00:08:21,534 --> 00:08:22,967
Why?

123
00:08:23,069 --> 00:08:24,866
Are you an actor?

124
00:08:24,971 --> 00:08:26,063
No.

125
00:08:26,172 --> 00:08:27,764
Are you an astronaut?

126
00:08:27,874 --> 00:08:28,932
No.

127
00:08:29,041 --> 00:08:30,975
Someone over there
would like to meet you...

128
00:08:31,077 --> 00:08:32,908
a young woman...

129
00:08:33,012 --> 00:08:35,537
only if you are none of these things.

130
00:08:39,952 --> 00:08:42,716
I'm Viscount Monteforte d'Alsace.

131
00:08:42,822 --> 00:08:44,517
- Willy.
- Don.

132
00:08:44,624 --> 00:08:46,922
This is Don.

133
00:08:47,026 --> 00:08:49,586
She's been staring at you all day.

134
00:08:49,695 --> 00:08:51,959
Can't stop talking about you.

135
00:08:53,165 --> 00:08:54,132
I'm Joy.

136
00:08:57,637 --> 00:09:00,333
And this is Rocci.

137
00:09:00,439 --> 00:09:04,603
You look so comfortable
alone by the pool all day.

138
00:09:04,710 --> 00:09:07,144
Made me wonder if you're
waiting for someone.

139
00:09:09,081 --> 00:09:10,708
I am.

140
00:09:11,884 --> 00:09:14,182
Do you smell that jasmine?

141
00:09:15,821 --> 00:09:17,015
Dine with us.

142
00:09:19,325 --> 00:09:20,553
Maybe another time.

143
00:09:20,660 --> 00:09:23,128
That never happens.

144
00:09:23,229 --> 00:09:24,526
Hello.

145
00:09:24,630 --> 00:09:26,996
Pete, this is Joy and Rocci

146
00:09:27,099 --> 00:09:29,033
and Viscount Monteforte.

147
00:09:29,135 --> 00:09:30,363
Very good.

148
00:09:30,469 --> 00:09:32,061
D'Alsace. Willy.

149
00:09:32,171 --> 00:09:33,798
That's quite a name.

150
00:09:33,906 --> 00:09:35,396
Peter Dykeman Campbell.

151
00:09:35,508 --> 00:09:37,499
Have we met somewhere? Newport?

152
00:09:37,610 --> 00:09:40,807
I have a terrible memory for faces.

153
00:09:40,913 --> 00:09:42,141
Nice meeting you.

154
00:09:42,248 --> 00:09:43,374
Yes.

155
00:09:43,482 --> 00:09:44,710
A pleasure to meet you.

156
00:09:48,621 --> 00:09:50,088
Look for us.

157
00:09:56,228 --> 00:09:59,322
Everybody here is late for everything.

158
00:09:59,432 --> 00:10:02,162
I just saw Tony Curtis in the men's room.

159
00:10:02,268 --> 00:10:04,327
Handing out towels?

160
00:10:04,437 --> 00:10:06,371
Tony Curtis, Don.

161
00:10:06,472 --> 00:10:08,099
A thing like that.

162
00:10:11,711 --> 00:10:13,269
Who's for dinner?

163
00:10:13,379 --> 00:10:14,471
Rodney Barnes.

164
00:10:14,580 --> 00:10:16,309
Classic salesman turned executive.

165
00:10:16,415 --> 00:10:19,680
And this interesting scientist,
Caleb Sawyer.

166
00:10:19,785 --> 00:10:22,185
He has this Optoman thesis.

167
00:10:22,288 --> 00:10:23,949
In addition to rockets,

168
00:10:24,056 --> 00:10:26,115
they're going to start engineering man...

169
00:10:26,225 --> 00:10:27,988
you know, for travel in space.

170
00:10:28,094 --> 00:10:31,359
New organs, super strength.

171
00:10:31,464 --> 00:10:33,398
You know the Soviets are working on it.

172
00:10:33,499 --> 00:10:35,763
Are all of our meetings like this?

173
00:10:35,868 --> 00:10:38,393
It's American Aviation and Rocketdyne.

174
00:10:38,504 --> 00:10:39,630
It's not a joke.

175
00:10:41,307 --> 00:10:43,275
Can I get a drink here or what?

176
00:10:53,986 --> 00:10:55,510
The Raphael was a little tired,

177
00:10:55,621 --> 00:10:59,022
but the Fifth Arrondissement
has most of your good restaurants.

178
00:10:59,125 --> 00:11:00,422
Of course, we kept getting lost,

179
00:11:00,526 --> 00:11:02,050
and every time Sherry asked for directions,

180
00:11:02,161 --> 00:11:04,152
it turned out to be another American.

181
00:11:04,263 --> 00:11:05,628
Well, there you go.

182
00:11:05,731 --> 00:11:08,996
I'll take Jane to Paris,
and I'll send Mona to Reno.

183
00:11:09,101 --> 00:11:10,534
You don't have to marry her, do you?

184
00:11:10,636 --> 00:11:12,263
No.

185
00:11:12,371 --> 00:11:15,966
Maybe you and Mona could work out
one of those modern arrangements.

186
00:11:16,075 --> 00:11:17,474
George, stop.

187
00:11:17,576 --> 00:11:21,103
It is possible that you'll get tired of her,
and then where will you be?

188
00:11:21,213 --> 00:11:22,976
Mona doesn't have a right to anything...

189
00:11:23,082 --> 00:11:24,982
not my company money,
not my family money.

190
00:11:25,084 --> 00:11:27,109
She's lucky I'm giving her anything.

191
00:11:27,219 --> 00:11:29,187
And you know what?
We've been miserable for years.

192
00:11:29,288 --> 00:11:30,880
I don't want to die with that woman.

193
00:11:30,990 --> 00:11:32,423
Calm down.

194
00:11:32,525 --> 00:11:35,323
I didn't know that.

195
00:11:35,428 --> 00:11:38,454
This is the life I was always meant to have.

196
00:11:39,999 --> 00:11:41,523
Congratulations.

197
00:11:43,369 --> 00:11:46,099
Mona has the marriage license,
and she wants to hurt you.

198
00:11:46,205 --> 00:11:48,901
If you want to be with this 20-year-old girl,
you're going to have to buy it from her.

199
00:11:49,008 --> 00:11:50,168
I have to warn you.

200
00:11:50,276 --> 00:11:53,837
Women in this situation
become extra irrational.

201
00:11:53,946 --> 00:11:55,413
Well, how badly
does she want to hurt me?

202
00:11:55,514 --> 00:11:57,106
I have a list of conditions

203
00:11:57,216 --> 00:12:00,117
and an alimony that could
support Rita Hayworth.

204
00:12:00,219 --> 00:12:02,619
Think of all the good things
in life and cut them in half.

205
00:12:02,722 --> 00:12:05,782
I want you to push as hard
as you can, but I want it done.

206
00:12:05,891 --> 00:12:08,121
Mr. Phillips is here.

207
00:12:08,227 --> 00:12:09,660
In a minute.

208
00:12:11,330 --> 00:12:12,695
I'll proceed.

209
00:12:12,798 --> 00:12:15,995
But I want you to think about it.

210
00:12:18,104 --> 00:12:20,038
Duck Phillips, this is George Rothman.

211
00:12:20,139 --> 00:12:22,198
Actually, we know each other.

212
00:12:23,375 --> 00:12:25,070
Roger.

213
00:12:25,177 --> 00:12:26,735
It's good to see you, Duck.

214
00:12:41,994 --> 00:12:43,359
Was he for you or against you?

215
00:12:43,462 --> 00:12:44,929
He's supposed to be the best.

216
00:12:45,030 --> 00:12:46,054
Him or Marvin Hughes.

217
00:12:46,165 --> 00:12:48,065
That's who Mona has.

218
00:12:48,167 --> 00:12:49,464
He's her cousin.

219
00:12:51,270 --> 00:12:53,534
How bad was it? Do I want to know?

220
00:12:53,639 --> 00:12:56,608
I don't think my circumstances
were the same as yours.

221
00:13:04,483 --> 00:13:05,507
What can I do for you?

222
00:13:05,618 --> 00:13:08,086
Actually, this might not be
the best time to talk about this.

223
00:13:08,187 --> 00:13:10,018
Can't you tell I'd welcome
a change in subject?

224
00:13:10,122 --> 00:13:11,919
Well, good, then.

225
00:13:13,392 --> 00:13:14,984
What the hell, right?

226
00:13:17,997 --> 00:13:20,761
Listen, we're coming up
on two years together here.

227
00:13:21,901 --> 00:13:23,163
Did you get me something?

228
00:13:27,173 --> 00:13:31,610
I think we're at a point in time
where I need to know what your plans are.

229
00:13:31,710 --> 00:13:34,338
A partnership. I think I've earned it.

230
00:13:36,415 --> 00:13:37,609
Right.

231
00:13:39,251 --> 00:13:42,709
I'll bring it up at the next meeting
of the partners.

232
00:13:42,822 --> 00:13:44,483
Thank you.

233
00:13:44,590 --> 00:13:47,559
Of course you might have to come in
and be an advocate for yourself.

234
00:13:47,660 --> 00:13:49,127
I'd be proud to present
my accomplishments.

235
00:13:49,228 --> 00:13:51,492
Good. Because I'm at a loss.

236
00:13:52,798 --> 00:13:54,459
What is that supposed to mean?

237
00:13:54,567 --> 00:13:57,434
You haven't exactly delivered
on that 30% you promised.

238
00:13:59,305 --> 00:14:01,603
I think we've really performed
in a very dismal year.

239
00:14:01,707 --> 00:14:03,732
These things are cyclical. You know that.

240
00:14:07,279 --> 00:14:09,747
Is there some question
about my value to Sterling Cooper?

241
00:14:09,849 --> 00:14:10,975
Just think about the board.

242
00:14:11,083 --> 00:14:12,744
Bert Cooper hates everyone.

243
00:14:12,852 --> 00:14:14,319
And his sister...

244
00:14:14,420 --> 00:14:16,479
well, she does whatever he says.

245
00:14:16,589 --> 00:14:19,285
Don, he's only 121/2%,

246
00:14:19,391 --> 00:14:22,326
but I can't say he's
your biggest cheerleader.

247
00:14:22,428 --> 00:14:23,827
What are you saying?

248
00:14:23,929 --> 00:14:25,453
Everyone thinks you're a fine fellow.

249
00:14:25,564 --> 00:14:30,024
But if I were you,
I'd go out there and make rain.

250
00:14:33,739 --> 00:14:36,037
Thank you for being so candid.

251
00:14:40,579 --> 00:14:43,309
This year we have seen
an historic collaboration

252
00:14:43,415 --> 00:14:44,848
in American aerospace.

253
00:14:44,950 --> 00:14:47,214
Building on Lockheed's new Polaris A3,

254
00:14:47,319 --> 00:14:48,809
Bell Aerosystems,

255
00:14:48,921 --> 00:14:50,513
Aerojet General, and NASA

256
00:14:50,623 --> 00:14:52,818
have developed a restartable rocket engine.

257
00:14:52,925 --> 00:14:55,155
Can we get the lights, please?

258
00:14:58,264 --> 00:15:00,095
We at Space Technology Laboratories

259
00:15:00,199 --> 00:15:04,226
have set our minds
to the challenges of the future.

260
00:15:04,336 --> 00:15:08,500
In July, Khrushchev said the Soviet Union
now has an anti-missile

261
00:15:08,607 --> 00:15:11,075
that can hit a fly in outer space.

262
00:15:11,176 --> 00:15:15,169
Space Technology Laboratories
is leading a coordinated effort

263
00:15:15,281 --> 00:15:17,181
to create an invulnerable warhead...

264
00:15:17,283 --> 00:15:19,581
multiple, independently targetable

265
00:15:19,685 --> 00:15:21,676
